<div class="content">
  <h2>Knife Essentials Guide</h2>
  <p>Building a quality knife collection starts with a few essential pieces. Avoid massive block sets filled with knives you'll never use. Instead, focus on these core tools:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>Chef's Knife (8-10 inches): The workhorse of the kitchen, used for chopping, slicing, and dicing most ingredients.</li>
    <li>Paring Knife (3-4 inches): Essential for detailed work like peeling, trimming, and intricate cuts.</li>
    <li>Bread Knife (Serrated): Designed with teeth to slice through crusty bread and delicate tomatoes without crushing them.</li>
    <li>Santoku Knife (Optional): A Japanese-style knife that excels at chopping vegetables with a straight up-and-down motion.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Sharpening Guide</h2>
  <p>Maintaining a sharp edge is crucial for safety and efficiency. A dull knife requires more force, increasing the risk of slipping.</p>
  <ul>
    <li>Honing (Weekly): Using a honing steel realigns the microscopic edge of the blade but doesn't remove metal. This keeps the knife feeling sharp between true sharpenings.</li>
    <li>Sharpening (Every 6-12 Months): Using a whetstone or electric sharpener removes metal to create a new edge. Whetstones offer the best results but require practice.</li>
    <li>Professional Service: If you're uncomfortable using a whetstone, sending your knives to a professional sharpener once a year is an excellent investment.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
  <div class="faq-list">
    <div class="faq-item">
      <div class="faq-q">What is the difference between German and Japanese knives?</div>
      <div class="faq-a">German knives are typically heavier with a curved blade for a rocking motion. Japanese knives are lighter with a straighter edge, designed for precise slicing.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="faq-item">
      <div class="faq-q">What does HRC hardness mean?</div>
      <div class="faq-a">HRC stands for Rockwell Hardness Scale C. A higher number means harder steel that holds an edge longer but is more brittle. Lower HRC means softer, tougher steel.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="faq-item">
      <div class="faq-q">Are expensive kitchen knives dishwasher safe?</div>
      <div class="faq-a">No. Always hand wash and dry premium kitchen knives immediately. Dishwasher detergents are abrasive and the environment can damage handles and dull edges.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="faq-item">
